Sports mode will not hurt your car in any scenario, it's not a race tune from an aftermarket tuner or some shit.

Basically, retarded grandmas with sloppy throttle pedal use don't want to get scared and yeet themselves through a grocery store entrance, so they default to "normal" mode that makes it delay a little bit when the accelerator is hit assuming you did so accidentally. It will also usually upshift sooner at lower RPM for best fuel economy. Sport mode, on the other hand, will make the car respond as fast as it is capable of and hold gears a little bit longer assuming you will want to keep accelerating even after lifting for a second, basically mimicking the behavior of a manual transmission and how it would be shifted. The only time/reason not to use sport mode is if the sport mode on your model keeps it from going into top gear or the highest CVT ratio, etc. and giving you worse MPG (I know BMW sport+ does this). As long as it will still go into the top gear, no reason not to use it if you find its behavior preferable.

Also of note is that sometimes sport mode is linked to firmer suspension settings if your car has adjustable shocks, so on shitty roads you will find the ride worse.

You can’t put a mileage on it. Rotors warp from hard stops followed by a quick cooldown, like hitting a puddle. Working for the feds. Generally blue collar positions like automotive mechanic won’t get GS, you’ll fall under the wage grade (WG) of the federal wage system because they’re paid hourly not salary. Automotive mechanic starts at WG-10 step 1 and maxes at WG-10 step 5 with no level increase to WG-11 or WG-12 unless you get promoted to work leader (11) and supervisor (12). Everything is public record, so you could go look up what WG-10 step 1 is in your area with the cost of living and locality pay already factored in. USA jobs also will typically show mechanic jobs with the auto generated “salary Range” showing step 1 through step 5 pay. With the upper range being the step 5 pay and lower being step one.
Retire is FERS/FRAE it’s something like average of highest three years of service multiple by years of service multiplied by 1.1%
So say you maxed out at 67,600$ (32.50 an hour, x80 hours x 26 Pay periods a year) and did 30 years of work you would get 22,308$ a year or roughly 1800$ a month. Ideally you’d also have a million in your federal TSP (401k) also because the pension ain’t that great
